2. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The paper discusses a multi-organizational system in which each organization contributes processors to the global pool but also jobs to be processed on the common resources. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed Computing sub-category. 
3. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper discusses the complexity of the fair scheduling problem and presents an FPRAS and an exponential algorithm. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms sub-category. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper discusses the stability and existence of the multi-organizational system and the importance of fairness in the scheduling algorithm. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Systems and Control sub-category. 
5. cs.LG (Machine Learning): Although the paper does not explicitly mention machine learning, the use of utility functions and the concept of strategy resilience are related to machine learning concepts. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning sub-category.
